<section xml:id="sec-calculating-2x2-inverses" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Calculating <m>2\times 2</m> inverses</title>

<p>
The next theorem tells us when a <m>2\times 2</m> matrix is invertible, and what its inverse is 
(if it has one).
</p>


<theorem xml:id="thm-invertible">
<statement>
<p>
A <m>2\times 2</m> matrix
<me>
A =
\begin{bmatrix}
  a \amp  b \\ c\amp d
\end{bmatrix}
</me>is invertible if and only if <m>ad-bc \neq 0</m>. In this case, we have
<me>
A\inv = \frac{1}{ad-bc}
\begin{bmatrix}
  d \amp  -b \\ -c \amp a
\end{bmatrix}
</me>.
</p>
</statement>

<proof>
<p>
Suppose <m>ad-bc\ne 0</m>. Then
<md>
<mrow>
A =
\begin{bmatrix}
  a \amp  b \\ c\amp d
\end{bmatrix}
\left(\frac{1}{ad-bc}
\begin{bmatrix}
  d \amp  -b \\ -c \amp a
\end{bmatrix}
\right) \amp  = \frac{1}{ad-bc}
\begin{bmatrix}
  a \amp  b \\ c\amp d
\end{bmatrix}
\begin{bmatrix}
  d \amp  -b \\ -c \amp a
\end{bmatrix}
\\
\amp  = \frac{1}{ad-bc}
\begin{bmatrix}
  ad - bc \amp  0 \\
  0       \amp  -cb+ da
\end{bmatrix}
\\
\amp  =
\begin{bmatrix}
  1 \amp  0 \\ 0 \amp  1
\end{bmatrix}
= I_2
</mrow>
</md>.
Similarly one can show that
<me>
\frac{1}{ad-bc}
\begin{bmatrix}
  d \amp  -b \\ -c \amp a
\end{bmatrix}
\begin{bmatrix}
  a \amp  b \\ c\amp d
\end{bmatrix}
= I_2
</me>.
This shows that <m>A</m> is invertible, with the desired inverse.
</p>

<p>
Conversely, suppose that <m>ad- bc = 0</m>.
</p>

<p>
<term>Case 1:</term> If <m>a = 0</m>, then <m>bc = 0</m>, so <m>b = 0</m> or <m>c = 0</m>. If <m>b = 0</m>,
<me>
\begin{bmatrix}
  0 \amp  0 \\
  c \amp  d
\end{bmatrix}
\begin{bmatrix}
  a' \amp  b' \\ c' \amp  d'
\end{bmatrix}
=
\begin{bmatrix}
  0         \amp  0 \\
  a'c + c'd \amp  b'c + dd'
\end{bmatrix}
\ne I_2
</me>
since the <m>(1, 1)</m>-entry is zero instead of one. If <m>c = 0</m>, then
<me>
\begin{bmatrix}
  a' \amp  b' \\ c' \amp  d'
\end{bmatrix}
\begin{bmatrix}
  0 \amp  b \\
  0 \amp  d
\end{bmatrix}
=
\begin{bmatrix}
  0 \amp  a'b + b'd \\
  0 \amp  bc' + dd'
\end{bmatrix}
\ne I_2
</me>. Since <m>a', b', c', d' \in \R</m> were arbitrary, this means that <m>A</m> has no inverse.
</p>

<p>
<term>Case 2:</term> If <m>a\ne 0</m>, then <m>d =\frac{bc}{a}</m>. Then, in the following Problem 
you are asked to show that
<me>
A =
\begin{bmatrix}
  a \amp  b \\ c \amp  \frac{bc}{a}
\end{bmatrix}
</me>
is not invertible.
</p>
</proof>
</theorem>

