<definition xml:id="def-2x2-determinant">
<statement>
<p>
The <term>determinant</term> of a <m>2\times 2</m> matrix
<me>
A =
\begin{bmatrix}
  a \amp  b \\ c\amp  d
\end{bmatrix}
</me>
is the real number <m>\det(A) = ad - bc</m>.</p>
</statement>
</definition>

<p>
Therefore <xref ref="thm-invertible"/> says that <m>A</m> is invertible if and only if 
<m>\det(A) \ne 0</m>, and in this case
<me>
A\inv = \frac{1}{\det(A)}
\begin{bmatrix}
  d \amp  -b \\ -c \amp  a
\end{bmatrix}
</me>.
So, to calculate the inverse of a <m>2\times 2</m> matrix, swap the elements on the diagonal, 
and negate the elements off the diagonal; then scale by <m>1/\det(A)</m>.
</p>

<example xml:id="ex-inv2">
<statement>
<p>
Determine whether the matrix is invertible and find the inverse if it exists for the following matrices:
<me>
A=
\begin{bmatrix}
  2 \amp  5 \\ 1\amp  3
\end{bmatrix}
, \qquad B =
\begin{bmatrix}
  1 \amp  -1 \\ -2 \amp  2
\end{bmatrix}
</me>.
</p>
<p>
First, <m>\det(A) = 2\times 3 - 5\times 1 = 1</m>, so <m>A</m> is invertible, with inverse
<me>
A\inv = \frac{1}{\det(A)}
\begin{bmatrix}
  3 \amp  -5 \\ -1 \amp  2
\end{bmatrix}
=
\begin{bmatrix}
  3 \amp  -5 \\ -1 \amp  2
\end{bmatrix}
</me>.
Second, <m>B</m> is not invertible since <m>\det(B) = 1\times 2 - (-1)(-2) = 2 - 2 = 0</m>.
</p>
</statement>
</example>


